excerpt: Hilltop fortress dating to 1219, now home to a history museum, youth hostel & restaurant.
detail_description: Veste Oberhaus is a historic hilltop fortress in Passau, Germany, dating back to 1219. It overlooks the town and the confluence of the Danube, Inn, and Ilz rivers. The fortress has never been conquered and was once the residence of the Bishop of Passau. Today, it houses a history museum, a youth hostel, a restaurant, and an open-air theatre.
name: Veste Oberhaus

excerpt: Baroque Catholic cathedral, designed by Carlo Lurag, with a gilded pulpit & frescoes by Tencalla.
detail_description: St. Stephan's Cathedral, a Baroque Catholic cathedral designed by Carlo Lurag, is a sight to behold with its gilded pulpit and frescoes by Tencalla. The cathedral houses the largest Catholic Church organ in the world, boasting an impressive 17,974 pipes and 233 stops. Visitors can enjoy organ concerts that showcase this technical marvel while admiring the stunning paintings on the ceiling, altar, and statues inside.
name: St. Stephan's Cathedral

excerpt: Passau, a German city on the Austrian border, lies at the confluence of the Danube, Inn and Ilz rivers. Known as the Three Rivers City, it's overlooked by the Veste Oberhaus, a 13th-century hilltop fortress housing a city museum and observation tower. The old town below is known for its baroque architecture, including St. Stephen's Cathedral, featuring distinctive onion-domed towers and an organ with 17,974 pipes.
detail_description: Passau, a charming German city located at the meeting point of the Danube, Inn, and Ilz rivers, is often referred to as the Three Rivers City. The city boasts the impressive Veste Oberhaus fortress on a hilltop, which houses a museum and an observation tower. Passau's old town is renowned for its stunning baroque architecture, including the iconic St. Stephen's Cathedral with its distinctive onion-domed towers and an organ featuring an astounding 17,974 pipes.
name: Passau

excerpt: Ornate clock tower & murals of knights in armor on the facade, plus large oil paintings inside.
detail_description: Passau Town Hall, located above the famous official residence square, is a typical German building with an ornate clock tower and murals of knights on its facade. The house was built in 1405 and features a gothic bell tower and large oil paintings inside. Historical figures of Passau are depicted on the facade, along with six figures holding flags representing different regions. Additionally, it houses the Passau Tourist Office's information center.
name: Passau Town Hall

detail_description: Höllgasse Artists Alley, also known as Passauer Kunstlergasse, is a charming cobblestone street in Passau lined with small studios, art galleries, and artisan shops. The alleyway offers a unique insight into the local art scene and is particularly recommended to visit during the artists' night. Colorfully painted stones along the way add to its artistic charm.
name: Höllgasse Artists Alley

detail_description: MMK Passau, also known as the Museum of Modern Art Wörlen in Passau, is a cultural gem located on the banks of the Danube. Founded by Hanns Egon Worlen, it boasts an impressive collection of modern art by both German and international artists. The museum serves as a bridge between East and West, showcasing cubist and expressionist works from local artist Georg Philipp Worlen.
name: MMK Passau - Museum of Modern Art Wörlen Passau

detail_description: Rathaus Altes Zollamt is located in the Altes Rathaus building, with an entrance on the side leading to the Grosser Rathaussaal. This hall features impressive 19th-century local paintings and offers a glimpse into the area's artistic heritage. Additionally, it serves as a convenient location for resolving administrative matters efficiently when all necessary documents are prepared.
name: Rathaus Altes Zollamt

detail_description: Step back in time and explore the Roman Museum Castle Boiotro, also known as the RomerMuseum Kastell Biotro. This museum, opened to the public in 1982, offers a glimpse into Passau's history during its time under Roman rule from 250 to 450 AD. Housed in a late medieval building, it showcases exhibits related to the East Bavarian region and Passau's history.
name: Roman Museum Castle Boiotro

detail_description: Glasmuseum Passau is a must-visit for glass enthusiasts, housing an extensive collection of over 30,000 pieces, including more than 1000 Loetz pieces. The museum's focus is on the art of glassmaking in the 19th century, offering detailed insights into production and development. Spanning four millennia of history, from ancient Egypt to modern times, this dazzlingly modern museum showcases exquisite handmade glass pieces with beautiful colors and designs.
name: Glasmuseum Passau

excerpt: Once used for defense & storage, this restored 13th-century riverside tower hosts occasional events.
detail_description: Schaibling Tower, also known as Schaiblingsturm, is a restored 13th-century riverside tower located in Passau along the banks of the river Inn. Originally built as a fortified tower for defense and storage, it has now been repurposed to host occasional events. The tower's striking white outline against the backdrop of the calm river makes for a picturesque sight. It served as protection against attacks and waves in the harbor while also storing powder and salt for trade.
name: Schaiblingsturm

excerpt: Traditional Bavarian haunt with hearty pub grub & beer, plus a spacious beer garden.
detail_description: Wirtshaus Bayerischer Löwe is a traditional Bavarian restaurant located in Passau, offering hearty pub grub and a variety of beers. The restaurant features a spacious beer garden and is centrally located in the city center. With its typical Bavarian decorations, heavy wooden tables, and friendly staff, it provides an authentic dining experience.
name: Wirtshaus Bayerischer Löwe

excerpt: Hilltop church with ornate towers & pilgrimage steps decorated with candles & portraits of saints.
detail_description: Perched on a hillside, Wallfahrtskirche Mariahilf is a stunning pilgrimage church with ornate towers and a courtyard adorned with candles and portraits of saints. Established in 1622, the complex underwent expansions throughout the 1600s. Accessible by foot via the Way of the Cross stairs or by car with free parking available, this well-maintained site offers a beautiful view of Passau from its top.
name: Wallfahrtskirche Mariahilf

excerpt: Set beneath a castle, this scenic area marks the confluence of the Inn, IIz & Danube Rivers.
detail_description: Located in Passau, Germany, the Three River Confluence is a picturesque area where the Danube, Inn, and Ilz Rivers meet. This spot is often referred to as the Three River City due to its unique location. Nestled beneath a castle and situated on the Altstadt peninsula, it offers stunning scenery and a tranquil atmosphere. Visitors can enjoy leisurely strolls along the riverside, observe boat traffic at the confluence point, and take in the beauty of this natural meeting place.
name: Dreiflüsseeck

detail_description: The Oberhausmuseum, located within the fortress in Passau, is a treasure trove of regional history dating back to medieval times. The museum offers stunning views of the confluence of three rivers and the surrounding regions. Visitors can explore the well-maintained bike paths nearby and enjoy a picturesque view of Passau from the castle. With an affordable entrance fee, it's worth visiting for its historical exhibits and breathtaking panoramas.
name: Oberhausmuseum

detail_description: Café Simon is a stylish and bright café located in Passau, offering a welcoming atmosphere to enjoy a rich selection of homemade chocolates, fine hot chocolate, and breakfast options. Visitors can indulge in coffee and cake, have a leisurely breakfast, or experience a relaxed brunch. The café provides ample seating, making it an ideal place for meeting up with friends or studying while enjoying complimentary Wi-Fi.
name: Café Simon

detail_description: ScharfrichterHaus Passau is a renowned historical restaurant in Passau, offering a traditional setting and cozy atmosphere. It's not just a place to dine; it also serves as a political cabaret where popular German comedians share their sharp-witted commentary on life. The restaurant offers high-quality, creative meals at reasonable prices, with friendly staff providing excellent service.
name: ScharfrichterHaus Passau

detail_description: Ludwigstraße is a bustling pedestrian-friendly shopping area located in Passau, offering modern shopping experiences. Visitors can explore the large and vibrant retail space, which is surrounded by a lively atmosphere. The street is easily accessible and provides an excellent opportunity for leisurely strolls and indulging in some retail therapy.
name: Ludwigstraße

detail_description: Cafe Lounge Diwan, located in the heart of Passau's Neue Mitte, offers a premium selection of coffee from around the world along with a wide variety of cakes, pastries, and pasta. The main attraction is its stunning panoramic view of Dreiflussestadt where the Danube, Inn, and Ilz rivers converge. Although reservations are not possible, lucky guests can secure seats by the window for an unforgettable experience.
name: Cafe Lounge Diwan

detail_description: Fritz-Schäffer-Promenade is a picturesque promenade that extends into the Danube, providing an ideal vantage point to observe passing ships.
name: Fritz-Schäffer-Promenade

detail_description: Viking River Cruises is a top-notch river cruise line that offers exceptional experiences along the Danube and other European rivers. Despite initial skepticism, travelers have been pleasantly surprised by the outstanding service and amenities provided on Viking's cruises. Even during challenging times such as the Covid pandemic, Viking has continued to deliver excellent experiences, earning high praise from passengers. The onboard care and attention to detail are consistently highlighted, with guests raving about the quality of food and overall experience.
name: Viking

detail_description: If you're looking for an unforgettable experience on the Danube, look no further than Kristallschiff – Donauschifffahrt Wurm & Noé. For just 17 Euros, you can embark on a delightful two-hour cruise that showcases the stunning beauty of the river and its surroundings. The ship itself is truly impressive, providing a comfortable setting to enjoy your journey. While there may be additional charges for extra plates or services onboard, many guests have found it to be a fantastic value overall.
name: Kristallschiff – Donauschifffahrt Wurm & Noé

detail_description: The Rathaus, or Town Hall, is a stunning architectural gem that often serves as the heart of a city. Typically characterized by its grand façade and intricate details, it stands as a symbol of local governance and community pride. Visitors are often captivated by its historical significance and the beautiful surroundings that make it an ideal spot for photos. Many Rathaus buildings also host cultural events, exhibitions, and markets throughout the year, providing a vibrant atmosphere for both locals and tourists alike.
name: Rathaus

detail_description: Nestled adjacent to the historic Old Town Hall, known as Rathaus, the Eingang Bürgerbüro Altes Rathaus offers stunning views of the nearby Castle right from its doorstep. This prime location also places visitors just a stone's throw away from the main boat docks, making it an ideal spot for those looking to embark on scenic river cruises. Whether you're exploring local history or setting sail on an adventure, this charming area is perfect for immersing yourself in the beauty and culture of your surroundings.
name: Eingang Bürgerbüro Altes Rathaus

detail_description: The Church of St Michael is a stunning attraction along the Inn Promenade in Passau. While it may be challenging to visit due to limited opening hours, glimpses through the lattice door reveal a splendid interior that offers a peaceful escape from the city's hustle and bustle. The church underwent an interesting architectural transformation from Gothic to Baroque after being damaged by fire, which can be observed in its exterior.
name: Church of St Michael

detail_description: Veste Niederhaus is a picturesque castle situated on a rocky headland at the confluence of the Ilz and Danube rivers in Passau. It forms a cohesive defensive system with the Oberhaus fortress, shaping the city's skyline. While it offers stunning views of the city and makes for great photo opportunities, it is unfortunately not open to the public as it is privately owned.
name: Veste Niederhaus

detail_description: Nestled behind the majestic cathedral in Passau, the Passauer Tölpel is a charming statue that adds a unique touch to your exploration of this picturesque city. While it may not be the main attraction, its quirky backstory—having fallen from the cathedral itself—adds an element of intrigue for curious travelers. As you wander through Passau's enchanting streets, filled with stunning architecture and scenic river views, don't miss this delightful figure.
name: Passauer Tölpel

detail_description: St. Gertraud Catholic church is a stunning place of worship, featuring a picturesque structure and a devout congregation. The priest and community exude deep spirituality, creating an atmosphere filled with reverence and devotion. It is highly recommended to join the Sunday morning mass at 10am for a truly enriching experience. The church offers a plethora of captivating sights that are sure to captivate visitors' interest. With its awe-inspiring ambiance and remarkable appeal, St.
name: Parish Church of St. Gertrude

detail_description: The Domschatz- and Diocesan Museum, also known as the Cathedral Treasure and Diocesan Museum, is a renowned institution founded in 1905. It is located in the old town of Passau on Residenzplatz. The museum showcases a remarkable collection of sacred art and treasures from Passau's history, including liturgical vessels, Byzantine staurotheke from the 10th century, books, and intricately decorated precious stones.
name: Domschatz- and Diocesan Museum

detail_description: The Denkmal für Ignaz von Rudhart is a remarkable tribute to an influential figure in Bavarian history. Born into a prominent family, Ignaz Rudhart's journey took him from his early life in Bamberg to significant roles in academia and government, including positions as a professor and ministerial councilor.
name: Denkmal für Ignaz von Rudhart

detail_description: Ehem. St.-Anna-Kapelle Kunstverein Passau is located in the former Franciscan monastery and showcases contemporary art in its impressive 450 square meter exhibition space. Visitors can enjoy a current exhibition featuring works by three artists, promising a delightful experience that will leave them smiling. The gallery is open from Tuesday to Sunday, offering free admission to all visitors. With a focus on always presenting beautiful exhibitions, this art venue provides an enriching cultural experience for art enthusiasts and tourists alike.
name: ehem. St.-Anna-Kapelle Kunstverein Passau

detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Passau, the Dreiflüssestadion is a charming old stadium that exudes character and history. While it may not always draw large crowds, its intimate atmosphere makes for an enjoyable experience, especially during local football matches. Visitors often appreciate the unique charm of this venue, making it a delightful spot to catch a game with family or friends.
name: Dreiflüssestadion
